<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38221a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38221a">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38221a"> 221(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Iran</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The fairy tale in The Nights is wholly and purely Persian. The gifted Iranian race, physically the noblest and most beautiful known to me, has exercised upon the world-history an amount of influence which has not yet been fully recognised &hellip; Hellas and <mark>Iran</mark> instinctively chose as their characteristic the idea of Beauty, rejecting all that was exaggerated and grotesque; and they made the sphere of Art and Fancy as real as the world of Nature and Fact. <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE1"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 127</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: In <cite>Finnegans Wake</cite>, Iran often is substituted for Erin, imparting to the Irish isle the connotations Burton praises. The titles of the songs &ldquo;Come back to Erin&rdquo; and &ldquo;Bold boys of Erin&rdquo; respectively become &ldquo;Come big to Iran&rdquo; (<cite>FW</cite> 144.18) and &ldquo;bold buoys of Iran&rdquo; (<cite>FW</cite> 491.36). ALP is an &ldquo;irished Marryonn Teheresiann&rdquo; (<cite>FW</cite> 538.1), at the same time the Blessed Virgin Mary, the empress Maria-Teresa, the Maid Marion of Robin Hood and an Irish girl who issues from Teheran, the capital of Persia; her name, incidentally, acknowledges some &ldquo;heresy.&rdquo; </mm> </dd></dl>
